ce:section.ce:para:
Various human biological fluids such as blood, plasma, saliva, mucus, and urine contain numerous biomarkers, including miRNAs, that are valuable for disease analysis [53]. In this study, we used human extracted serum to evaluate the efficiency of nanostructured biosensor to detect the target miR-223. Diluted concentrations of miR-223 were analyzed using the fabricated biosensor with two-percent serum of human (in ratio of 50:1 diluted in PBS). Selecting a 2% dilution concentration for serum in biosensor experiments reduces interference from proteins, follows standard practices, minimizes matrix effects, and may impact sensitivity and detection limit, suggesting potential benefits in testing different dilution concentrations to optimize biosensor performance in detecting target analytes. The results obtained from the DPV technique for human serum in PBS containing microRNA-223 are presented in Fig. 9
                           , with the estimated RSD and error bar for the bare electrode (NS platform, or working electrode), microRNA-223, microRNA diluted in human serum with PBS, and DNA capture probe. The RSD percentage was low for all mentioned repeats, indicating that the Au-GQDs based immunosensor is acceptable analytical tool for microRNA-223 detection assays, even in human real samples. This immunosensor shows promise for application in CRC clinics and its early diagnosis. The detection of micro-RNAs from real samples through nano-fabricated biosensors is crucial for early disease detection. We compared the efficiency of our electrochemical biosensor with recently reported strategies that utilize nanomaterials-based biosensors for miRNA detection (Table 2
                           ). For instance, a paper-based voltammetric approach for miR-155 and 21 detection showed a lower limit of detection (LOD) compared to our biosensor (12.0–25.7 nano M for gold-NPs/RGO and 51.6–59.6 nano M for gold-NPs/MoS2 immunosensors) [54]. However, the portability of their immunosensor is an advantage in comparison to our sensor, which requires a readout platform. Another study by Shahbazi-Derakhshi et al. demonstrated that the performance of their biosensor improved when AuNPs were decorated on the perovskite GO nanocomposite substrate in their study, Khosravi and colleagues (2023) created an immunosensor to detect miR-155 through electrochemical procedures. The biosensor they developed utilized a nanocomposite composed of functionalized and conjugated graphene materials, gold nanostars, and nickel–iron NPs for enhanced detection capabilities [55]. Their biosensor also had a lower LOD compared to ours, but our biosensor is simpler and does not require the fabrication of complex systems. One major challenge in using nanofabricated-based working electrodes is having a nanofabrication protocol for detection approaches that can produce stable and reproducible electrodes with high electroactivity, without the need for surfactants. Furthermore, our immunosensor is a label-free biosensor that exhibits great capability for miRNA detection in both standard and human real samples. The fabrication of label-free immunosensors through electrochemical techniques is crucial because the presence of enzymes, chemical agents, and labeling agents can compromise result accuracy, potentially causing false-positive or false-negative conclusions.
